Set up the function to import and clean the data

json_import <- function(json_file_path) {
  

  # download the data
  file_path <- paste("Data/", substr(json_file_path, 50, 91), sep = "")
  download.file(json_file_path ,  file_path)
  
  # Take the date out of the file name
  date <- substr(file_path, 16, 25)
  
  # split out the date
  month <-
    month(ymd(010101) + months(month(date) - 1),
          label = TRUE,
          abbr = TRUE)
  year <- year(date)
  
  # import data and keep only the category
  json_data <- stream_in(file(file_path))
  
  # handle the different file formats
  if (year <= 2017) {
    #2,3 data.category_name
    json_data <- as_tibble(json_data$data$category_name)
  } else {
    json_data <- as_tibble(json_data$data$category)
  }
  
  # categories we're finding for Gaussian distribution
  categories <-
    c(
      'Education',
      'Energy & Green Tech',
      'Health & Fitness',
      'Fashion & Wearables',
      'Wellness'
    )
  
  # only keep the categories needed
  json_data <- json_data %>%
    filter(value %in% categories)
  
  
  
  # add dates to data
  json_data$year <- year
  json_data$month <- month
  json_data$occurences <- 1
  
  # remove null rows
  json_data <- json_data %>% drop_na()
  
  # print details for tracking
  print(paste("Date",date,"| NRows Imported:",nrow(json_data)))
  
  # return the data
  input_data <- json_data
}

Download and import the files.

for (k in 1:length(data_urls)) {
  if (k == 1) {
    input_data <- json_import(data_urls[1])
  }
  else {
    input_data <- rbind(input_data, json_import(data_urls[k]))
  }
}

Aggregate the data.

grouped <- input_data %>%
  group_by(value, month, year) %>%
  summarise(count_occurences = sum(occurences))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'value', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Test if distribution is gaussian.

education <-  grouped %>% filter(value == 'Education')
energy <-  grouped %>% filter(value == 'Energy & Green Tech')
health <-  grouped %>% filter(value == 'Health & Fitness')
wellness <-  grouped %>% filter(value == 'Wellness')
fashion <-  grouped %>% filter(value == 'Fashion & Wearables')

Interpretation of the Shapiro test and Q-Q Plots

Some of the distributions appear to be normally distributed based the Shapiro test scores and Q-Q plots.

Firmly a Gaussian distribution:

  • Energy: p = .11 > .05

Likely a Gaussian distribution:

  • Education: p = .084 > .05
  • Wellness: p = .068 > .05

Not a Gaussian distribution:

  • Health: p = .001 < .05
  • Fashion: p = .0029 < .05

Details for Shapiro test:

  • Null Hypothesis = normally distributed
  • Alternate Hypothesis = not normally distributed
  • If p > a then accept null hypothesis
  • If p </= a then reject H0 in favor of HA.
  • Must reject the null hypothesis if p < 0.05
# Likely a normal distribution since p = .084 < .05
shapiro.test(education$count_occurences)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  education$count_occurences
W = 0.81758, p-value = 0.08409
# Normal distribution, p = .11 > .05
shapiro.test(energy$count_occurences)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  energy$count_occurences
W = 0.85674, p-value = 0.1114
# Not a normal distribution, p = .001 < .05
shapiro.test(health$count_occurences)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  health$count_occurences
W = 0.68118, p-value = 0.001377
# Likely a normal distribution, p = .068 > .05
shapiro.test(wellness$count_occurences)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

W = 0.83591, p-value = 0.06837
# Not a normal distribution, p = .0029 < .05
shapiro.test(fashion$count_occurences)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

Compare following two categories: Health & Fitness, Fashion & Wearables on year basis (2018, 2019, 2020).

Create the data set for testing, being sure to sort the data so it is in the same order.

health <- arrange(health, year, month)
x <- health$count_occurences

fashion <- arrange(fashion, year, month)
y <- fashion$count_occurences

With three statistics tests, one parametric, two non-parametric tests and report results.

One parametric test

The p value is greater than significance level of 0.05. This means we should not reject the null hypothesis, meaning the distributions appear to be similar. This test wouldnt be correct to perform because the earlier tests showed this doesnt appear to be a Gaussian/normal distribution. A non-parametric test would be more appropriate.

t.test(x,y)

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  x and y
t = 0.23666, df = 13.395, p-value = 0.8165
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -4215.706  5256.456
sample estimates:
mean of x mean of y 
 4560.375  4040.000

Two non-parametric

The p value is greater than significance level of 0.05. This means we should not reject the null hypothesis, meaning the distributions appear to be similar.

ks.test(x,y, exact = FALSE)
p-value will be approximate in the presence of ties

    Two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test

data:  x and y
D = 0.25, p-value = 0.9639
alternative hypothesis: two-sided
wilcox.test(x,y, exact = FALSE)

    Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction

data:  x and y
W = 36, p-value = 0.6946
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

Use an effect size test to quantify the magnitude of differences.

Cohens D test result indicates that the effect size is small

cohen.d(x,y,return.dm=TRUE)

Cohen's d

d estimate: 0.1183303 (negligible)
95 percent confidence interval:
     lower      upper 
-0.9550011  1.1916617

Use three correlation coefficient tests (Pearson, Spearman, KendallTau) and report whether following two keywords have correlations: Fashion & Wearables, Health & Fitness.

All three tests are either 1 or almost 1. This result indicates a very strong increasing monotonic relationship.

cor(x, y, method = "kendall")
[1] 1
cor(x, y, method = "pearson")
[1] 0.9992117
cor(x, y, method = "spearman")
[1] 1

A density plot of the two distributions backs up the test results. They appear to be largely similar.

plot(density(x))                             
lines(density(y), col = "red")
